4. Creating a Repository

mkdir git-lab
cd git-lab
git init
ls -a  # shows .git directory

5. Git Architecture & Workflow

Git uses three main areas:

Working Directory: where you edit files

Staging Area (Index): files prepared for commit

Local Repository: commits stored permanently

Workflow Example:

edit file → git add → git commit

6. File States

State	Description

Untracked	New file not yet tracked
Modified	Tracked file changed
Staged	Ready to commit
Committed	Snapshot saved in repository

Check status:

git status

7. First Commit (Lab)

touch app.txt
echo "Hello SRE" >> app.txt
git add app.txt
git commit -m "initial commit"
git log : commit 6f0b320a2cb55a3b17dccd00663b9732da2171d3 (HEAD -> master)

8. Adding Files

git add file.txt       # stage a specific file
git add .              # stage all files
git status             # check staged files

9. Viewing Commit History

git log                  # full commit history
git log --oneline        # short version , Ex: 6f0b320 (HEAD -> master) initial commit
git log --graph --oneline --all   # graph view
git show <commit_id>     # detailed info

10. Git Diff

git diff                 # changes in working directory. Will see an + or - if there was a change.
git diff --staged        # staged changes : Shows what you have staged (added) but not yet committed
git diff <commit1> <commit2>   # compare commits in history

11. Undoing Changes

git restore file.txt                  # discard changes in working directory (Line by line)
git restore --staged file.txt        # unstage changes (Removes the file from the staging area (undo git add))
git revert <commit_id>               # safely undo a commit. Will create a new commit.
git reset --hard <commit_id>         # reset to previous commit (dangerous since You lose uncommitted changes)

git reset --hard 6f0b320
# HEAD now points to 6f0b320, all later commits gone

12. Branching

git branch                      # list branches
git branch feature-login        # create branch
git checkout -b feature-login   # create & switch
git switch feature-login        # alternative to checkout
git checkout main               # switch branch
git branch -d feature-login     # delete branch safely
git branch -D feature-login     # force delete
git branch -m old-name new-name        # rename branch

13. Merging Branches

git checkout main
git merge feature-login

Meaning:

Move to main
Bring changes from feature-login into main

Merge Types: 

Fast-forward merge: Happens when main has not changed since the branch was created.
No commits were added to main while working on the other branch so no conflict.

Merge commit (no fast-forward): Occurs when both branches have new commits

14. Merge Conflicts

When conflicts occur:

A conflict occurs when Two branches modify the SAME line in a file

Git doesn’t know which version to keep → you must decide manually.

<<<<<<< HEAD
code from current branch
=======
code from feature branch
>>>>>>> feature-login

Resolve Steps:

Edit conflicted files (Remove conflict markers and choose the correct code)
You can:

Keep one version
Combine both
Rewrite completely

Stage changes (Stage the resolved file): git add file

Complete the merge: git commit

Check conflict status: git status

15. Remote Repositories

Common platforms: GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket

They allow teams to share code, collaborate, and deploy.


git clone <repo_url>            # copy/download remote repo to your machine
git remote add origin <url>     # add/link remote repo to your local repo.
git remote -v                   # view remotes
git remote remove origin        # remove remote

16. Push & Pull                 # This is how you sync local ↔ remote

git push origin main            # push branch

In case of failures due to that the remote has commits local does not have:

git pull origin main
git push origin main

git push -u origin main         # set upstream so next time you can just do: git push
git push --all origin           # Pushes ALL your local branches to the remote (origin)
git pull origin main            # Downloads AND merges changes from remote main
git fetch                       # downloads changes from remote without merging
git push --tags                 # Pushes all tags to remote

Example:

git tag v1.0
git push --tags

git diff origin/<branch> compares your local branch with your remote branch (main)

 git branch -r: shows remote branches:

ubuntu@ubuntu-vm:~/git-lab$ git branch -r
  origin/main

Align your local branch with remote:

git checkout master
git branch -m master main        # rename local branch to main
git fetch origin
git diff origin/main             # see differences
git pull origin main             # merge remote changes into local master

If you do have local commits, Git may create a merge commit.

If you want to make your local branch exactly the same as remote (discard local changes), use:

git fetch origin
git reset --hard origin/main

17. Stashing


Temporarily save uncommitted changes:

git stash                  # Useful when you need to switch branches, pull updates, or test something quickly without losing your work.

Leaves your working directory clean.

git stash list             # list stashes 
git stash show <stash_id>  # view stash changes and details
git stash show -p stash@{0} # See full details
git stash apply <stash_id> # Restores the changes (to the working directory) without removing the stash.
git stash pop              # apply and remove stash: Restores changes and deletes the stash.
git stash drop <stash_id>  # delete stash
git stash clear            # delete all stashes

Note: You CANNOT apply a stash if the same file is already modified

Example:

# Save your changes temporarily

- Takes your uncommitted changes
- Saves them in a stash
- Cleans your working directory

Command: git stash save "WIP hotfix"

# Pull latest changes safely

- Fetches changes from remote (origin)
- Merges them into your local branch (main)

Command: git pull origin main

# Restore your work

- Takes your saved changes from stash
- Applies them back into your working directory
- Deletes the stash

Command: git stash pop


18. Tags (A tag is a label attached to a specific commit)

git tag -a v1.0 -m "first release" # This attaches v1.0 to your current commit
git tag # List tags
git show v1.0  # Show tag details
git push --tags # Push tags to remote (Tags are NOT pushed automatically with git push)

If something breaks (rollback):

git checkout v1.0  : Instantly go back to a stable version

19. Advanced Git (Senior SRE Focus)

Git Rebase # Instead of merging, it moves your commits on top of another branch
git rebase main

Linear history, cleaner logs

Example

You have:

main:      A---B---C
feature:        D---E

Run:

git rebase main

Result:

main:      A---B---C
feature:            D'---E'

👉 Your commits are reapplied on top of main



Git Cherry-Pick # Takes one specific commit and applies it to your current branch.

git cherry-pick <commit_id>

Apply a specific commit, useful for hotfixes

git checkout main
git cherry-pick abc123

Only that commit is copied into main

If cherry-pick pauses → just:
git add .
git cherry-pick --continue

Git Reflog (Recovery) # Shows every action you've done locally, even deleted commits.

git reflog   
git reset --hard HEAD@{2}   # Restores your repo to that state/commit
Git Bisect (Debugging) # Finds the exact commit that introduced a bug using binary search.
git bisect start
git bisect bad              # current version is broken
git bisect good <commit>    # known good version

Summary:

Rebase      → clean history
Cherry-pick → copy one commit
Reflog      → recover lost work
Bisect      → find buggy commit

20. Git Troubleshooting (SRE Section)

Recover deleted commit:

git reflog # shows a history of where your HEAD (and branches) have been
git reset --hard <commit> : This command moves your current branch AND working directory back to a specific commit.

Undo bad merge:

git reset --hard HEAD~1 # Moves your branch one commit back (Completely removes the last commit)

Restore deleted file:

git checkout <commit> -- file.txt

Takes file.txt from a specific commit
Restores it into your current working directory

👉 It does NOT change your branch, only that file

Find bug introduction commit:

git bisect  # Finds the exact commit that introduced a bug using binary search


21. Production Workflow Example

git checkout -b fix-memory-leak # Never work directly on main in production systems
git add .
git commit -m "fix: memory leak in worker"
git push origin fix-memory-leak  # Uploads branch to remote repository

Workflow:

Create branch → Implement → Commit → Push → PR → Review → Merge → Deploy

